# Java ThreadLocal - Short Notes

## What is ThreadLocal?

`ThreadLocal` provides a separate copy of a variable for each thread.

Normally, instance variables belong to an object and are shared when multiple threads use the same object.

With `ThreadLocal`, the value belongs to the thread instead of the object.

---

## Why Do We Need ThreadLocal?

### Shared Object

```java
class Counter {
    int count = 0;
}

Counter c = new Counter();

Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> c.count++);
Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> c.count++);
```

Memory:

```text
Thread-1
      \
       --> Counter Object (count)
      /
Thread-2
```

Both threads share the same `count`.

---

### Using ThreadLocal

```java
ThreadLocal<Integer> count =
        ThreadLocal.withInitial(() -> 0);
```

Memory:

```text
Thread-1 -> count = 10
Thread-2 -> count = 20
Thread-3 -> count = 30
```

Each thread gets its own value.

---

## Important Methods

### set()

```java
threadLocal.set("Lalit");
```

Stores a value for the current thread.

### get()

```java
String name = threadLocal.get();
```

Gets the value of the current thread.

### remove()

```java
threadLocal.remove();
```

Removes the value associated with the current thread.

---

## Same Object + Multiple Threads

```java
class MyTask implements Runnable {

    private ThreadLocal<Integer> count =
            ThreadLocal.withInitial(() -> 0);

    @Override
    public void run() {

        count.set(count.get() + 1);

        System.out.println(
                Thread.currentThread().getName()
                + " -> " + count.get());

        count.remove();
    }
}
```

```java
MyTask task = new MyTask();

Thread t1 = new Thread(task);
Thread t2 = new Thread(task);
Thread t3 = new Thread(task);
```

Output:

```text
Thread-0 -> 1
Thread-1 -> 1
Thread-2 -> 1
```

Even though all threads use the same object, each thread has its own value.

---

## Internal Working

Each thread maintains its own `ThreadLocalMap`.

```text
Thread-1
   |
   ---> ThreadLocalMap
          user -> Lalit

Thread-2
   |
   ---> ThreadLocalMap
          user -> Rahul
```

The value is stored inside the thread, not inside the `ThreadLocal` object.

---

## ThreadLocal in Thread Pool

ThreadLocal is commonly used with thread pools.

```java
ExecutorService pool =
        Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);
```

Example:

```java
private static ThreadLocal<String> user =
        new ThreadLocal<>();
```

```java
try {
    user.set("Lalit");

    // business logic

} finally {
    user.remove();
}
```

### Why remove() is Important?

Thread pool threads are reused.

```text
Task 1 -> Thread-1 -> user = Lalit

Thread-1 returns to pool

Task 2 -> Thread-1
```

Without `remove()`:

```java
user.get();
```

Output:

```text
Lalit
```

Task 2 may see old data left by Task 1.

Always use:

```java
try {
    threadLocal.set(value);

} finally {
    threadLocal.remove();
}
```

---

## Real-World Uses

* User Session Information
* Database Connections
* Transaction Management
* Security Context
* Request Context

Frameworks like Spring use ThreadLocal internally.

---

## Instance Variable vs ThreadLocal

| Feature                  | Instance Variable | ThreadLocal |
| ------------------------ | ----------------- | ----------- |
| Belongs To               | Object            | Thread      |
| Shared by Threads        | Yes (same object) | No          |
| Requires Synchronization | Often Yes         | No          |
| Separate Copy            | Per Object        | Per Thread  |

---

## Interview Points

1. `ThreadLocal` gives each thread its own copy of a variable.
2. Values are isolated between threads.
3. Main methods: `set()`, `get()`, `remove()`.
4. Value is stored inside the thread (`ThreadLocalMap`).
5. Useful when multiple threads use the same object but need separate data.
6. Commonly used with thread pools.
7. Always call `remove()` in thread pools to avoid stale data and memory leaks.

### Easy Analogy

```text
Instance Variable -> Locker belongs to Object

ThreadLocal -> Locker belongs to Thread
```

Each thread gets its own private locker (value).

NOTE = ThreadLocal → Each thread gets its own private value.

InheritableThreadLocal → Same as ThreadLocal, but when a child thread is created, it automatically receives a copy of the parent's value. This inheritance happens only at thread creation time, not when thread-pool threads are reused.

